Package software.kes.gauntlet

Class Arbitrary<A>

  • java.lang.Object
    • software.kes.gauntlet.Arbitrary<A>
  • Type Parameters:
    A - 
    public final class Arbitrary<A>
extends java.lang.Object
    An Arbitrary differs from a Generator in that an Arbitrary adds the following capabilities:
    • Can be filtered
    • Can carry a shrinking strategy
    • Can carry a custom pretty-printer

    When composing Arbitrarys, the underlying filters, shrinking strategies, and pretty-printers will be composed as well.

    An Arbitrary cannot be fmapped or flatMapped like a Generator can be. However, if you have an Iso<A, B>, you can convert an Arbitrary<A> to an Arbitrary<B>.

    Several built-in Arbitrarys can be found in the Arbitraries class.

    You can always create an Arbitrary from any Generator, no matter how complex, but you will have to provide your own shrink strategy (if shrinking is desired).

      • suchThat

        public Arbitrary<A> suchThat​(com.jnape.palatable.lambda.functions.Fn1<? super A,​java.lang.Boolean> predicate)
        Creates a new Arbitrary that filters its output. Note that a filtered Arbitrary is not guaranteed to ever return a value that satisfies its predicate, so some safety mechanisms are in place to prevent it from running infinitely.

        If after a number of tries, the Arbitrary cannot produce a value, it will fail with a SupplyFailure and the test will fail abnormally. The maximum number of tries can be controlled using withMaxDiscards(int).

        Returns:
        a new Arbitrary that is the same as this one, with the added filter

      • withMaxDiscards

        public Arbitrary<A> withMaxDiscards​(int maxDiscards)
        Sets the maximum number of successive tries that a filtered Arbitrary will make in order to produce a single value before failing with a SupplyFailure. Once a value is produced, the counter will be reset.

        This value will be respected even if you set it before any calls to suchThat(com.jnape.palatable.lambda.functions.Fn1<? super A, java.lang.Boolean>).

        Returns:
        a new Arbitrary that is the same as this one, with the max discards set to the provided value
